  "verdict": "RESOLVED BY A BASE-METRIC CHANGE. The log-Euclidean (flat, zero holonomy) base metric lifts the worst weak-jump x strong-drift corner AUC from 0.65 (square-root, path-wise) to 0.96 (>= 0.85) while keeping jump power on genuine strong collapses at 0.90 (>= 0.80). Because log-Euclidean is FLAT -- zero holonomy -- a strong geodesic drift can no longer manufacture the holonomy pseudo-jump that fooled the square-root statistic, so the weak collapse separates from the drift. The Exp D corner is therefore a SQUARE-ROOT-CONNECTION (holonomy) limit that a flat base metric repairs -- exactly the base-metric change the Hybrid probe said was required, and which no same-geometry statistic could supply. The base-linearized square-root control confirms the corner is holonomy: folding the path into the base frame lifts it 0.65 -> 0.92, i.e. discarding the holonomy alone removes the confusion. Paper 3 Sec 6.4 should name log-Euclidean (flat, zero holonomy) as the drift/jump-robust base metric in the weak-collapse x strong-drift corner. (Supplementary, base-linearized Bures-Wasserstein: worst corner 0.91, power 0.97 -- optimistic, since its holonomy is not path-wise-transported.)",
